#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:632
msgid "What can this plugin do and how does it work?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:637
msgid "This plugin is privacy-oriented: optimization runs on your server and does not require sending your site data to third-party services."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:639
msgid "WP Optimizer is modular, so you can enable only the features you need to keep the plugin overhead low."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:641
msgid "Server enhancements such as compression, browser caching, and server rules."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:642
msgid "Caching layers for queries, database results, objects, and static pages."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:643
msgid "Minification for HTML, CSS, and JavaScript."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:644
msgid "Local image optimization and conversion workflows."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:645
msgid "Database cleanup, optimization, and backups."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:646
msgid "Security hardening and WordPress behavior toggles."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:647
msgid "Update controls, diagnostics, logs, and admin utilities."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:649
msgid "Because modules can affect different parts of WordPress, the safest approach is to enable one feature at a time and test the front end after each change."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:656
msgid "What should I enable first on a live site?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:660
msgid "Start with lower-risk optimizations, then move to the more aggressive ones only after testing."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:662
#, php-format
msgid "Begin with <a href=\"%s\">browser cache and compression settings</a> because they usually improve delivery without changing page logic."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:663
#, php-format
msgid "Configure <a href=\"%s\">media optimization</a> for new uploads before launching large bulk jobs."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:664
#, php-format
msgid "Create a <a href=\"%s\">database backup</a> before cleanup tasks or bigger tuning sessions."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:665
#, php-format
msgid "Add <a href=\"%s\">cache</a> and <a href=\"%s\">minify</a> last, enabling one option at a time and verifying the front end after each step."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:673
msgid "Where can I configure optimization parameters?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:677
#, php-format
msgid "Most optimization options are configurable in the <a href=\"%s\">Modules Options panel</a>."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:678
#, php-format
msgid "Global tasks such as cron, module activation, telemetry, reset, export, and restore are available from the <a href=\"%s\">Settings page</a>."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:685
msgid "Can cache or minify break my layout?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:689
msgid "Yes. Aggressive caching and front-end minification can expose conflicts in themes or plugins that rely on specific asset order, inline scripts, or dynamic output."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:691
#, php-format
msgid "Enable <a href=\"%s\">minify</a> gradually: HTML, CSS, and JavaScript do not need to be turned on all at once."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:692
#, php-format
msgid "After each change, clear or reset <a href=\"%s\">cache</a> and test important pages while logged out as well."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:693
msgid "If something breaks, disable the last option you enabled first. That is usually the fastest way to isolate the conflict."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:701
msgid "How does the media optimizer work?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:705
msgid "Media optimizer works in three different ways:"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:707
#, php-format
msgid "By a scheduled event it's able to collect and optimize any media uploaded daily. <a href='%s'>Here</a> you can configure all schedule related settings."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:708
msgid "By a specific path scanner, Media optimizer will run a background activity to optimize all images present in the input path."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:709
msgid "By a whole database scanner, Media optimizer will run a background activity to check all images saved in your WordPress library optimizing each image and every thumbnail associated."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:711
#, php-format
msgid "Any image optimization will be run following your settings set <a href=\"%s\">Here</a>."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:718
msgid "Why are image optimization jobs not starting?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:722
msgid "Bulk image optimization runs in background, so it depends on the plugin scheduler and on image libraries available on the server."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:724
#, php-format
msgid "Verify that <a href=\"%s\">cron is active</a>; background jobs will not progress if scheduled tasks are not running."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:725
msgid "Check that Imagick or GD is available in PHP. Imagick gives the best coverage, but GD can still handle basic processing."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:726
#, php-format
msgid "Review your <a href=\"%s\">media settings</a> before starting a full-library scan so the job uses the correct quality and format options."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:734
msgid "Do I need Redis or Memcached for object cache?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:738
msgid "Only the object cache feature requires Redis or Memcached. The other optimization modules can still be used without them."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:740
#, php-format
msgid "If your server does not provide Redis or Memcached, leave <a href=\"%s\">object cache</a> disabled."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:741
msgid "Static page cache, database/query cache, browser cache, compression, and minify do not depend on an external object cache server."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:749
msgid "How can I clean the database safely?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:753
msgid "Database cleanup is most useful when you do it conservatively and with a rollback path ready."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:755
#, php-format
msgid "Create a fresh <a href=\"%s\">database backup</a> before deleting revisions, transients, orphaned data, or other leftovers."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:756
#, php-format
msgid "Run cleanup tasks from the <a href=\"%s\">Database module</a> when the site is stable and no import, migration, or major update is running."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:757
msgid "If the result is not what you expected, restore the backup first instead of guessing which rows changed."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:765
msgid "Can I export settings before major changes?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:769
#, php-format
msgid "Yes. The <a href=\"%s\">Settings page</a> lets you export, import, reset, or restore plugin options."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:770
msgid "Use an export before testing aggressive cache, minify, or security changes so you can quickly return to a known-good configuration."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:777
msgid "Does WP Optimizer work on multisite?"
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:781
msgid "Yes. The plugin supports multisite and can be network-activated."
msgstr ""

#: admin/PagesHandler.class.php:782
#, php-format
msgid "Even on multisite, test optimization changes gradually from the <a href=\"%s\">module settings</a> because each subsite may use different themes, plugins, and traffic patterns."
msgstr ""

